#Procrisis_Adj_Data is the resulting object of merging all the closing adjusted prices for all the stocks. N of rows=1258 days (5 years)\ N of cols= 40 companies
ProCrisis_Adj_Data <- do.call(merge, eapply(Adj_Data, Ad))

Addition of logs

Here it cointains the proces of filling in an empty matrix with the closing stock price for each company, we add logs to the division of t=1 between t=t-1 for each day

#empty matrix
log_mat<- matrix(,nrow = nrow(ProCrisis_Adj_Data)-1,ncol = ncol(ProCrisis_Adj_Data))

#we convert ProCrisis_Adj_Data to a matrix for coding purposes.
test <- as.matrix(ProCrisis_Adj_Data)

#LOOP to fill the empty matrix. As the first day doesn-t have a previous day, we start the loop at day 2.(2:1258)
for (i in 2:1258) {
  for ( j in 1:40) {
    log_mat[i-1,j]<- (log(test[i,j]/test[i-1,j]))
  }
}

Matrix of Sample Correlations

Creation of the correlation matrix(COR) between stocks(columns of log_mat)

COR<- matrix(,nrow = 40,ncol = 40)
COR<-(cor(log_mat))

BOOTSRAP

Implementation of the bootstrap procedure for B=1000

n<- nrow(log_mat)
bsamp<- matrix(,nrow = nrow(log_mat),ncol = ncol(log_mat))
btheta<- matrix(,nrow = 40,ncol = 40)
B = 1000

#Vector where all the bootstrap samples are saved. cointains the matrices of correlations from the bootstrap sample
brep = c()

set.seed(1213)  
for (b in 1:B){
  idx = sample(1:n, replace = T)
  bsamp = log_mat[idx,]
  #btheta is the correlation matrix of every bootstrap sample
  btheta<-cor(bsamp)
  #btheta is stored in brep
  brep[[b]]<- btheta
}

DELTAS

Creation of the delta values for each bootstrap sample. For each bootstrap sample we define the bootstrap replicate of a simulataneous test statistics

deltas <-c()

for (i in c(1:B)){
  deltas <- append(deltas,sqrt(n)*max(abs(brep[[i]]-COR)))
}
#plot of the bootstrapped ECDF
Gstar = ecdf(deltas)
plot(Gstar,main="")

hist(deltas, breaks = 25, col = "orchid", border = "white",
     xlab = expression(hat(rho)[boot]),
     main = "Bootstrap approximation \n to the sampling distribution")

###Confidence Intervals We create the sets of confidence intervals for the correlation between stocks for alpha=0.05. Conf_set_1 contains the lower confidence intervals Conf_set_2 contains the upper confidence intervals

alpha = 0.05
ta = quantile(deltas,c(alpha/2, 1-alpha/2))
conf_set_1 <- COR-ta[2]/sqrt(n)
conf_set_2 <- COR+ta[1]/sqrt(n)

ta

###Marginal Correlation Matrix for epsilon=0.15

g<-make_empty_graph(length(stocks))
for(i in 1:length(V(g))){
  V(g)$name[i]=stocks[i]
  g<-set.vertex.attribute(g,"group", stocks[i], GICS[i])

ε = 0.15

#we use the following for loops so that wedon't take the same pair of correlations two times
for (i in 1:39){
  for (j in (i+1):40){
    #if the intersection of the upper and lower confidence intervals for a pair of stocks doesn't fall in the interval range of [-ε,+ε], we add an edge to that pair.
    if ( conf_set_1[i,j]>=ε |  conf_set_2[i,j]<= -ε){
      
          g=add.edges(g,c(stocks[i],stocks[j]))
          g=as.undirected(g)
    }   
}
}
#plotting of the graph
plot(g, lwd= 6, vertex.color=pal[as.numeric(as.factor(vertex_attr(g,"group")))])

As we see in the graph above, for an ε of 0.15 or smaller, almost all the stocks have edges between them, due to the fact that their confidence intervals don’t fall in [-0.15,0.15] We appreciate that a main group cointaining almost all the stocks. There is another one with few stocks that semm to be not correlated at all, and the last one has a few stocks from the same GICS, dark blue Consumer Staples and light blue Consumer Discretionary. ###Marginal Correlation Matrix for epsilon=0.30

Marginal Correlation Graph based on distance covariance

g2<-make_empty_graph(length(stocks))
for(i in 1:length(V(g2))){
  V(g2)$name[i]=stocks[i]
  g2<-set.vertex.attribute(g2,"group", stocks[i], GICS[i])
}


for(i in 1:(ncol(log_mat)-1)){
  for (j in (i+1):ncol(log_mat)){
    #in this marginal correlation graph we get the pvalues from an independence test between the pairs of stocks, and if that pvalue is less than alpha=0.05, we reject H0 (H0=distance covariance=0) and we add an edge to that pair.
    testcase=indep.test(log_mat[,i],log_mat[,j],method = "dcov",R=1000,index = 0.001)
    #testcase[5] = pvalue
    if(testcase[5] <alpha){
      g2=add.edges(g2,c(stocks[i],stocks[j]))
      g2=as.undirected(g2)
    }
    
  }
}
plot(g2, lwd= 6, vertex.color=pal[as.numeric(as.factor(vertex_attr(g2,"group")))])

We observe in the above graph that there are too many stocks that have edges amongst them, no matter their sectors.This can be explained because there is a huge amount of pairs that we are testing, so randomness really affects our results. ###Marginal Correlation Graph based on distance covariance with BONFERRONI Correction

g5<-make_empty_graph(length(stocks))
for(i in 1:length(V(g5))){
  V(g5)$name[i]=stocks[i]
  g5<-set.vertex.attribute(g5,"group", stocks[i], GICS[i])
}

#we add bonferroni correction to the previous loop
for(i in 1:(ncol(log_mat)-1)){
  for (j in (i+1):ncol(log_mat)){
    testcase=indep.test(log_mat[,i],log_mat[,j],method = "dcov",R=1000,index = 0.001)
    if (p.adjust(testcase[5],method = 'bonferroni',n = factorial(ncol(log_mat))/(factorial(38)*factorial(2))) <alpha){
      g5=add.edges(g5,c(stocks[i],stocks[j]))
      g5=as.undirected(g5)
    }
    
  }
}

plot(g5, lwd= 6, vertex.color=pal[as.numeric(as.factor(vertex_attr(g5,"group")))])

We were expecting boferonni to give us more solid results, but id didnt, because we see that in this graph we have no edges at all.The reason for this is we are making a false assumption in the very beggining of he homework. We have the adjusted prices for each stock during a period of many years, but we treat all the observations as IID variables,although they form a time-series, thus they are not independent.I think its logical to say that the value of a stock in any given day, it will affect its price in the next day also.
